Discriminated unions in TypeScript use a common property (the discriminator) to distinguish between different types in a union. TypeScript can then narrow the type based on the discriminator's value. For state management, this pattern creates type-safe state objects:
typescript
type State =
  | { status: 'idle' }
  | { status: 'loading' }
  | { status: 'success'; data: string }
  | { status: 'error'; error: Error }

function handleState(state: State) {
  switch (state.status) {
    case 'idle':
      // TypeScript knows state is { status: 'idle' }
      break;
    case 'loading':
      // TypeScript knows state is { status: 'loading' }
      break;
    case 'success':
      // TypeScript knows state has a 'data' property
      console.log(state.data.toUpperCase());
      break;
    case 'error':
      // TypeScript knows state has an 'error' property
      console.error(state.error.message);
      break;
  }
}

This approach eliminates runtime type checking and provides compile-time safety.

A type predicate function in TypeScript uses a return type annotation of `value is Type` to tell TypeScript what type a value is when the function returns true. Here's how to check for strings:
typescript
function isString(value: unknown): value is string {
  return typeof value === 'string';
}

// Usage example:
const unknownValue: unknown = 'hello';
if (isString(unknownValue)) {
  // TypeScript now knows unknownValue is string
  console.log(unknownValue.toUpperCase());
}

This is cleaner than using `typeof` checks throughout your code and provides better type safety.

Indexed access types allow you to extract specific types from other types using bracket notation. For example, given a `User` type, you can extract the type of its `email` property:
typescript
type User = { id: string; name: string; email: string };

// Extract the type of the 'email' property
type UserEmail = User['email']; // string

// Extract all possible keys
type UserKeys = keyof User; // 'id' | 'name' | 'email'

// Extract the value type of a specific key
const user: User = { id: '1', name: 'Alice', email: 'alice@example.com' };
type EmailType = typeof user['email']; // string

These techniques help keep your types DRY and automatically update when the source type changes.

You can create a mapped type that transforms all properties of a type to be nullable. Here's how:
typescript
type User = { id: string; name: string; age: number };

// Make all properties nullable
type Nullable<T> = { [K in keyof T]: T[K] | null };
type NullableUser = Nullable<User>;

// Resulting type: { id: string | null; name: string | null; age: number | null }

// Usage example:
function getUser(): NullableUser {
  return {
    id: null,      // Could be missing
    name: 'Alice', // Present
    age: null      // Could be missing
  };
}

This pattern is useful when dealing with data that might be partially available or when working with APIs that sometimes return null values.
